faqs:
  - q: "What is self-employment tax and why is it so high?"
    a: "Self-employment tax is 15.3% of net self-employment income — 12.4% Social Security plus 2.9% Medicare. Employees split this with their employer, but freelancers pay both halves. Only 92.35% of net is subject, so the effective rate is closer to 14.13%."
  - q: "How much should I reserve for taxes as a freelancer?"
    a: "A common heuristic is 25–30% of net self-employment income (gross minus business expenses). The right number depends on your federal bracket, state tax, and deductions. The companion guide on freelancer tax reserves walks through the breakdown."
  - q: "Which expenses can I deduct?"
    a: "Ordinary and necessary business expenses — software, mileage, home-office portion, equipment, professional services, and similar items. Document everything; the deduction has to be substantiated if reviewed. Talk to a tax professional for borderline cases."
  - q: "Do I really need to make quarterly estimated payments?"
    a: "Yes, if you expect to owe a meaningful amount in tax for the year. The IRS expects tax paid as you earn it. Missing quarterly payments can trigger underpayment penalties. The tool estimates the total annual liability you can divide into four quarterly payments."
  - q: "Does the calculator handle state tax?"
    a: "It uses simplified state-tax assumptions for a few common states and a generic 5% for 'Other'. For accurate state planning, look up your state's actual brackets — California, New York, and several others have multi-bracket systems that this tool simplifies."
